Homework 3: Is Donald Trump going to win the republican nomination?

This homework is due Tuesday March 8, 2016 at 8PM EST. When complete, submit your code in an R Markdown file and the knitted HTML via GitHub.

Motivation

In 2012 Nate Silver, and other data scientists, predicted the outcome of each state correctly. They did this by aggregating data from many polls to create more precise estimates than what one single poll can provide.

In this homework, we will try to predict the results of the democratic and republican primaries by studying the performance of polls in elections that already occurred and then aggregating results.

The first step in our analysis will be to wrangle the data in a way that will simplify the analysis. Ultimately, we want a table of results with each poll represented by a row and including results for each candidate as well as information about the poll such as name and date.

Problem 2E

Consider the Trump - Rubio difference. For each poll in IA, NH, SC and NV, compute the error between the prediction and actual election results. Use exploratory data analysis to get an idea of how time and pollster impacts accuracy.

results_error<-results%>%
   filter(state%in%c("IA","NH","NV","SC"),is.na(diff)==FALSE)%>%
   mutate(error=diff-adiff)
#error<-results_error$error
#end_date<-results_error$end_date
#hist(error)
#plot(end_date,error)
#abline(h=mean(error))
results_error%>%
  ggplot(aes(error))+geom_histogram(bins=40)+geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(error), color = "red"))

results_error%>%
  ggplot(aes(end_date,error))+ geom_smooth(span=0.5)+geom_point()

results_error%>%
  group_by(house)%>%
  filter(n()>4)%>%
  ggplot(aes(house,error,fill=house),)+geom_boxplot()

From the histogram, we can find that the error is not really normally distributed and is skewed. From the scatterplot, we can find that the error is increasing as the final date approaches. More and more point tend to have positive error as time goes. From the boxplot, we can find that errors in different survey houses are quite different, both in the mean value and the standard deviation. Clearly, time and pollster impact the accuracy.

Problem 3

Before seeing any polls my prior belief is that Rubio will beat Trump in Florida. If I were to quantify this belief I would say that the distribution of the Trump - Rubio was normal with mean \(\mu=-20\) percent and standard deviation \(\tau=10\). Let’s call the difference \(\theta\). Then

\[ \theta \sim N( \mu, \tau) \]

Problem 3A

Under my prior belief, what is the chance that Trump would beat Rubio in Florida.

mu_prior=-20/100
tau_prior=10
1-pnorm(0,mu_prior,tau_prior)
## [1] 0.4920217

Problem 3B

Consider the latest 25 Florida polls. Assume the poll results for the difference are normal distributed with mean \(\theta\) and standard deviation \(\sigma\). Provide an estimate for \(\theta\) and an estimate of the standard deviation \(\sigma\).

results_fl<-results%>%
  filter(state=="FL")%>%
  arrange(desc(end_date))
results_fl%>%
  filter(end_date>="2015-09-13")%>%

##   theta_hat  sigma_hat

## 1    0.1676 0.06917851

\[ \hat{\theta} \sim N( \theta, \sigma/ \sqrt{25})\]

Now use the Central Limit Theorem to construct a confidence interval.

ci_parameter<-results_fl%>%
  filter(end_date>="2015-09-13")%>%
  summarize(theta_hat=mean(diff),sigma_hat=sd(diff),tot_poll=n())
ci_parameter$theta_hat+c(-1,1)*(ci_parameter$sigma_hat/sqrt(ci_parameter$tot_poll))*qnorm(0.975)
## [1] 0.1404825 0.1947175

Problem 3C

Combine these two results to provide the mean and standard deviation of a posterior distribution for \(\theta\).

N <- ci_parameter$tot_poll
B <- (1/tau_prior^2) / (N / ci_parameter$sigma_hat^2 + 1/tau_prior^2)
sd_post <- sqrt( (1 / tau_prior^2 + N / ci_parameter$sigma_hat^2)^(-1) )
mu_post <- mu_prior * B + ci_parameter$theta_hat * (1-B)
mu_post

Here, we ignore the time effect and house effect. We assume that these effects will not affect the results largely.

However, we could also use election results and poll results in those states that already have results to evalute the time effect and house effect. Here we choose to ignore them.

N <- tabEst$tot_poll
B <- (1/tau_prior^2) / (N / tabEst$sigma_hat^2 + 1/tau_prior^2)
sd_post <- sqrt( (1 / tau_prior^2 + N / tabEst$sigma_hat^2)^(-1) )
mu_post <- mu_prior * B + tabEst$theta_hat * (1-B)

So in FL, the probability of Trump beating Cruz is

1 - pnorm(0, mu_post, sd_post)
## [1] 1

We can confirm it by Monte Carlo simulation.

N = 100
set.seed(1234)
qplot(rnorm(N,mu_post,sd_post), geom = "histogram", bins = 20, 
      xlab = "difference between Obama and McCain in FL")

mean(rnorm(N,mu_post,sd_post)>0)
## [1] 1
N = 100 
B = 1e4
result <- replicate(B, {
    X <- mean(rnorm(N,mu_post,sd_post) > 0)
})
qplot(result, geom = "histogram", bins = 20, 
      xlab = "Probability that Obama beats McCain in FL") + 
    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(result), color = "red")) + 
    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 1 - pnorm(0, mu_post, sd_post), color = "blue"))

So Trump is more likely to win in FL.

B <- (1/tau_prior^2) / (N / tabEst$sigma_hat^2 + 1/tau_prior^2)
sd_post <- sqrt( (1 / tau_prior^2 + N / tabEst$sigma_hat^2)^(-1) )
mu_post <- mu_prior * B + tabEst$theta_hat * (1-B)

The probability of Trump beating Cruz is

1 - pnorm(0, mu_post, sd_post)
## [1] 1

We can confirm it by Monte Carlo simulation.

N = 100
set.seed(2)
qplot(rnorm(N,mu_post,sd_post), geom = "histogram", bins = 20, 
      xlab = "difference between Obama and McCain in NC")

mean(rnorm(N,mu_post,sd_post)>0)
## [1] 1
N = 100 
B = 1e4
result <- replicate(B, {
    X <- mean(rnorm(N,mu_post,sd_post) > 0)
})
qplot(result, geom = "histogram", bins = 20, 
      xlab = "Probability that Obama beats McCain in NC") + 
    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(result), color = "red")) + 
    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 1 - pnorm(0, mu_post, sd_post), color = "blue"))
